Way back in slavery time, I would stand after the people were free.

I forgot his name.
But then I knew he looked like Yankee White.
That's what he used to do when he was young.
Well, then they come, and my old master, O'Connor McRae, he brought two of the horses for him.
I rode the horse many times.
One of them was a big horse they called Yankee Tom, a big, solid horse.
And another big old horse was a saddle horse O'Connor McRae bought, and he was called Boston.
He was a good, big, black horse.
He took them all down to the farm.
He took all of that.
Good big boys, eh?
Good big boys.

I said, I'm glad Noah got acquainted with you because I believe he's a good man and I want him to be with a good man.
Well, tell me, where were you born, Uncle Bob?
I was born not far from this place, up here south, west of here, about five miles.

Nothing more than hymns, hymns.
He was a regular church man.
Well, what kind of songs did you sing when you were young?
Well, I didn't just holler reels, just fiddle reels, you know, all the time, my singing.
Were you a fiddler yourself?
No, sir, no, sir.
I couldn't make no music at all.
Well, you could make music with your mouth.
Oh, yes, I could do that.
I sure would do that.
Everywhere you'd hear me, you'd hear me singing a song, a reel.
And out in the field, what'd you do when you were working?
That's what I'd do, hollering, singing reels.

About Little Joe?
Yeah.

Now, you told me about the man that you worked for for 10 or 12 years, Mr. Norwood.
And you said he's the meanest man in the country.
Well, they said so.
Them Norwoods worked for the meanest people in the world around them.
Well, how did it treat you?
It treated me all right.
The nine one of them never did cuss at me the whole 12 years.
I didn't care what I went to them for, I got it.
Bowels of flour, middles of meat, chags of molasses, money any time.
Now that Judge Noah, as the oldest boy, if his store would be full of hands, you know, he was more than old to know what he was doing.
I'd just tell him, give me a pencil and a piece of paper.
He'd hand it to me, and I'd write it on there and tell him, I want a $5 piece of it.
I'd hand it to him, go on by my business.
First thing you know, he'd come on by me, text me, and give it to me.
He'd do me that way just to show me, just to show me that I'm a leader.
What was it the old merchant, what was it the old merchant told you?
You told the old merchant down here, Mr. Mooringford.
Me and him was talking down one day and wasn't nobody in there but me.
I say exactly what you said now.
Yes, but wasn't nobody in there but me and him and his son and his son's daughter.
And I said, Mr. Corrigan,
I forgot exactly how old I was, but anyhow, I said, I'm 61 or two years old, and I never had no trouble in my life.
I said, I never asked the noise for nickel, but they didn't give it to me, in my life.
And that one of them never accosted me.
And said, I ain't never been summoned, and ain't never been arrested, and ain't never been to the jailhouse but twice in my life, and ain't been to the courthouse but twice.
He looked at me and cooked.
He said, well, Bob, I'm down.
That ain't too much for a nigga to say.
He said, ain't no white man can say any better than that.
He said, ain't.
I said, well, I'm telling you the truth.
I said, you can ask these people all around the school that know me, and they'll tell you I ain't never been in no trouble since I've been there.

Did they put you in jail or what?
No, I just went by there.
Went by the jail?
Down the street, yes.
Well, when you had friends in jail, didn't you go to see them?
I didn't go to see them because I always said, practice makes perfect.
I cried, I said so, and I just wouldn't go to see them.
I said, no, I ain't going to see them.
I said, practice makes perfect.
I ain't going there.
The Lord knows I'm telling you the truth, what I said.

I never went to school a day in my life, not an hour.
Hey, hey, hey, howdy, howdy, howdy, howdy, yeah.

Well, nobody here can tell you I never went to school an hour in my life.
Well, uh... Well, go ahead.
Dr. Noah, I never went to school an hour in my life.
Not an hour.
Well, then could you read and write?
I could read and write, too.
I could send a letter all over this world if I just knew where to send it.
Of course, I can't write it pretty like people do, but anywhere I know where to send it, I can send it.
Well, how'd you learn to write?
Well, my daddy just taught me how to spell a little at night.
Well, after that, then he took a corpus, and I took a corpus and just learned myself.
And how'd you learn to read?
Well, he learned at night.
He said he wasn't no educated man.
He could just read print, and he'd sit up at night and teach his children.
That's the way we learned.
I heard a story about a judge asking a colored boy on the witness stand.
He said, Jim, can you read writing?
He said, no, sir, judge.
I can't even read reading.
But you can read reading and write and go.
And they had a preacher who was trying to make a preacher out of him.
And I asked him, could he, did he know, did he know theology?
He said, no, sir, I never knew that man in my life.
I never been crazy with him.
So I don't know about no, nothing like that.
How old were you when you joined the church?
I was 19 years old.
And how old were you when you got married?
Oh.
Just in between it.
Just started in between it.
Well, did your wife make you join the church?
No, sir.
Let's join myself.
Let's tuck a motion and join myself.
Well, how have you got along so well in life?
What's been your principles?
Well, people are after people.
Anybody you know around here hasn't bought my principles.
I just went on.
I just like and know what a right to do and I always try to do what's right.
Well, that's a mighty good way to do it, Pa.
Yes, sir.
I know what's right and I try my best to do what's right in everything I do.
How many times have you voted?
Ain't voted but twice.

And another thing that I remember on the plantation that we hadn't mentioned before was the churning song.
Little Emma, the baby's nurse, after the baby was tucked in bed, was often called in the kitchen to do the churning.
And this is a song that she sang to the milk.
Come, butter, come, Mr. standing at the gate, waiting for the butter cake to come, butter, come.
Come, butter, come, Mr. is waiting.
Come, butter, come, Mr. is waiting.
Come, butter, come, the Mrs. is waiting.
Come, butter, come, the Mrs. is waiting.
Mrs. is waiting for the butter cake to come, butter, come.
And this chant would go on through until the churning was finished and the rich golden butter would come into a solid cake on the top of the mill.
the meeting day at Oak Grove Church.
The first Sunday in August was a gala occasion for the Negroes on the place.
That was the day the big practice meeting began over at Oak Grove Baptist Church, a day of parade for the new dresses, new suits, new hats, for each Negro was dressed out in his Sunday dress.
About 10 o'clock in the morning, they would be on their way to church,
And it looked as if the divets of white, pink, blue, red, yellow, and the variegated colors had outrivaled themselves in putting out the brightest colors of which their dresses were made from.
Every pattern wrote on the plate was filled with those who were going to church.
